Tyrisia L Carpenter was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Tyrisia L Carpenter was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

for hearing on 7-7-14
  Envelope: Return to Sender - Not Deliverable as Addressed - Unable to Forward.

Defendant Tyrisia L Carpenter in court, in custody, with attorney Joan B Broughton.   District Attorney Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin. 

Defendant needs ID processing.  

Atty. Broughton states that her client was serving a probation revocation that was up on July 22, 2014 but has not been released.  Atty. Broughton has acknowledged the governor's warrant on this case.  Atty. Broughton requests bail be revoked and returned to the poster.  Atty. Broughton further requests the court leave the 7-7-14  hearing date on to make sure the defendant is in Illinois.  

Court advises and defendant waives right to an attorney, right to file writ and right to an extradition hearing.    Court revokes bail and orders it  refunded to poster. Court approves the extradition.
Extradition Request from the State of Illinois with attached Governers warrant filed by the State
Warrant for Commitment signed by Judge Bohren on 6-11-14

Defendant is not to use/possess any controlled substances without a valid prescription and take as prescribed.  Defendant not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  Defendant is not to operate a motor vehicle unless properly licensed.

Defendant Tyrisia L Carpenter in court, in custody, with attorney Joan B Broughton.   Timothy Suha appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  State is waiting for governor's warrant to be processed.  Atty. Broughton makes statements that the defendant planned to turn herself into Illinois.  Defendant will be released from custody on June 22, 2014 and would then go to Illinois to resolve the matter.  Atty. Broughton requests a review after June 22, 2014.  State is requesting a warrant for commitment.  Atty. Broughton objects.  Defendant agrees she is the person wanted in Illinois.    Court advises of right to an attorney and acknowledges she does have an attorney present.  Atty. Broughton is not yet waiving extradition.  Court signs warrant for commitment.   Court maintains bail as set.
